{  
 "response_text": "Cumulative livestock destocking across the 60 households follows a monotonically increasing trajectory over the 100-year simulation horizon, beginning at zero and accumulating to approximately 97 animals per household by the conclusion of the period. The rate of accumulation exhibits distinct phase transitions rather than constant linear growth.\n\nDuring the initial approximately 25 years, destocking proceeds rapidly with steep annual increments, reflecting sharp reductions from the initial stocking level of 90 animals as households respond to immediate pasture conditions and implement their respective learning strategies. By the first change point around year 25, the cumulative total reaches roughly two-thirds to three-quarters of its final value, indicating that the majority of herd reduction occurs within the first quarter of the simulation.\n\nFollowing this initial phase, the accumulation rate decreases substantially entering the middle period spanning roughly years 25 to 60. Throughout this interval, destocking continues but at moderating velocities, with multiple inflection points concentrated between years 45 and 60 suggesting fluctuating adjustment speeds as experiential and social learning processes refine stocking decisions. The slope stabilizes at progressively lower values through successive decades, indicating diminishing annual destocking requirements as management strategies adapt to local ecological conditions and household risk dispositions.\n\nAfter approximately year 60, the trajectory enters a final phase characterized by minimal yet persistent annual destocking at rates near 0.3 animals per year. This prolonged tail suggests continued fine-tuning of herd sizes or ongoing mortality management under stationary conditions, with households approaching terminal herd configurations significantly below initial stocking levels. The absence of peaks or plateaus confirms the irreversible nature of cumulative destocking, while oscillatory patterns with a dominant period near 49 years embedded within the accumulation rate likely reflect cyclical responses to rainfall variability driving periodic adjustments in stocking rates.\n\nThe final cumulative value of approximately 97 animals indicates that, on average, households turned over their complete initial herd plus additional stock over the century, consistent with conservative stocking strategies emerging from learning-based adaptation to highly variable rainfall regimes in the absence of livestock reproduction."
}

